Class 1 Recap

  1. If you havent done so already, please register y our attendance. You can find the link to the attendance sheet on the class2 channel on slack.

  2. Change the name of the author in the YAML part (the top of the notebook) to your name.

  3. Create atomic vectors of type character, integer and logical. Call them anything you like, they can be of any length.

beverageNames <- c("ginger ale", "orange juice", "tea")
beverageQuantity <- c(5, 8, 10)
beverageSugar <- c(T, T, F)
  1. Use typeof() to confirm the type of data held by the three atomic vectors you created.
typeof(beverageNames)
[1] "character"
typeof(beverageQuantity)
[1] "double"
typeof(beverageSugar)
[1] "logical"
  1. Use length() command to find the lengths of each vector
length(beverageNames) 
[1] 3
length(beverageQuantity)
[1] 3
length(beverageSugar)
[1] 3

  1. Find and read the help pages for the colon shorthand :. You can either search for it using the Help tab on the bottom right pane or using the command ?colon. Ignore the part about the factors.

  2. Replicate the examples at the bottom of the help page i.e.copy paste and run them in a chunk. Ignore the examples for factors (the ones that use the gl() command).

pi:6 # real
[1] 3.141593 4.141593 5.141593
6:pi # integer
[1] 6 5 4
  1. Explain in a couple of short sentences why c("one", 1) yields the atomic vector ["one", "1"].

Arrange a table

flights %>%

library(tidyverse); library(nycflights13)
flights%>%
arrange(desc(time_hour))
  1. Arrange the flights data in descending order of dates (the last day of the year should be the first row of the data). You just have to print this, no need to save it to a new variable. Use the tidyverse portal and/or google to find the answer (if you dont know it already).

flights %>% 
  select(year, month, day, contains("delay"))

Filter rows

  1. Select the first three columns (year, month, day), all other columns whose names contains() the term delay and the origin column. Filter this data to show only the month of December. Assign this new tibble to a variable. Make sure to use pipes between the select and filter command. Refer to the shortcut for inserting a pipe.
  2. Filter the tibble you create in step 1 to show only those flights that took from JFK that took off in the AM.
  3. Use top_n() to find the most delayed departures from NYC in 2013. No need to save this. Just print out.
  4. Fix this code
flights %>% 
    filter(month = 6 & day > 15)
